		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I... smell a topic split. <br /><br />This laptop isn't really good enough to have Aero enabled (nor can it get better drivers than what I've got), but that's not why I disabled it at first. I just prefer the solid colors and no title bar transparency. I want my UIs as plain as possible. I liked Windows Office better before the ribbon and gradients as well. I make NES games, like old GUIs, and live in a place much earlier than 1996. I think most who are part of this community do in at least some small way.<br /><br />But even if my computer was good enough for me to not feel the performance loss, I still wouldn't want my GUI to use any more CPU than it has to. It'd be cool if whenever I buy a new computer, the GUI doesn't take the same percentage of CPU as it did on the old computer because of gloss that doesn't help me get tasks done. I can deal with tearing, and I've only ever encountered a few &quot;problem programs&quot; that must be run in Aero to use at all... (constant alternating between a black screen and what it should be, or just black all the time. Sort of like what's described in <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?f=5&amp;t=9612&amp;p=104743&amp;hilit=flicker#p104736" class="postlink">this post.</a>)<br /><br />Re: Aero's thick borders. That was another concern of mine, but you CAN just make them smaller. Annoyingly (at least on Vista), those options give you a preview of what the changes you're making will look like in the classic theme and not the Aero theme... You have to constantly apply and adjust to see what they look like in Aero. I actually did customize the size and color of the various parts of windows when I was using XP, but now I don't bother. <br /><br />I'm sure you can get solid color title bars and the other things I like with clever theming. But eh... going through all that when classic is close to what I want is silly.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
