		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Drag wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">7 allows you to (very easily) shrink the borders back down to 0. Even if it didn't, mobile screens have been experiencing a gradual increase in DPI (Remember when your cellphone used to have a 48x32 display?).</div><br />Android has &quot;density&quot; and &quot;area&quot; as concepts, where the pixel size of an element is the length (in <a href="https://developer.android.com/guide/practices/screens_support.html" class="postlink">dp</a>) times the density (how many physical pixels per dp). Increase in DPI means that user interface elements will grow larger in pixels so that they stay visually the same. Windows has this as well, provided your <a href="http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/dd464646%28v=vs.85%29.aspx" class="postlink">program is DPI-aware</a>.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And even though it's very popular to think developers are idiots, I <em>think</em> they would realize they've made a mistake when they've made the borders so big that they literally cover a quarter of the screen.</div><br />Touch interfaces on very small screens like those of phones (for a GUI, 10 cm/4 inches diagonal is very small) need to have big borders separating one touchable control from another.<br /><br />Might Microsoft's big push for WinRT (and a monopoly app store) be part of why Valve has expanded Steam to Linux and introduced Big Picture (a ten-foot UI)?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


