		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Oh, so you're no longer working at Microsoft and now you're complaining about all of this ?</div><br />The only reason I brought up the fact I worked there for 5 years is because it validates that I'm not making shit up, i.e. I didn't install Windows 7 for 15 minutes + &quot;didn't like the difference&quot; + roll back to XP.  This is specifically in regards to Drag's words: &quot;but what's so bad about getting used to them, other than &quot;oh no, it's different&quot;?&quot;  This was not a case of &quot;oh its different, screw it&quot; -- I seriously had to use this crap for 5 years (2 for Vista, 3 for Windows 7).<br /><br />The fact that I worked at Microsoft has absolutely zero bearing on the bugs at hand too.  People often think &quot;because you work at company X, you can do something about some bugs!&quot;  Sadly it's untrue.  There are quite literally <strong>hundreds</strong> (I would say quite literally 400-500) of teams/divisions at Microsoft internationally, with no easy way to track down who's responsible for what.  On an off-day I spent a few hours trying to figure out what team was handling these kinds of issues and was unable to determine who to contact or how to bring these issues to light internally; e.g. there is no team called &quot;Windows 7 UI Dev Team&quot;.  Welcome to the corporate world.<br /><br />There's also the PR aspect.  We had very strict nation-wide conduct compliance rules pertaining to blog and forum posts relating to Microsoft products.  Even disclaimers like &quot;I speak for myself and not on behalf of my employer&quot; do not matter -- if you work for company X and say &quot;yeah, product Y from company X could be better&quot;, you're effectively acting as a spokesperson for the company and that can get you into trouble with HR.  I did have this happen WRT something I said on a public forum, but it wasn't with regards to any Microsoft software products (it was with regards to a customer of ours who claimed I was &quot;disclosing confidential information&quot; about a service outage on their network -- an internal review conducted concluded I was not disclosing confidential information, but for PR/company image reasons I was asked to have the forum moderator nuke the contents of my post).  Again: welcome to the corporate world.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Yes, I miss the theme, I liked &quot;Rainy Day&quot; and another one I don't remember. However you can still change the colours manually if you wish, while keeping in the classic windows look, so it's not that bad.</div><br />Like I said: there are many Windows Appearance and Colour options which either have no effect or cannot be changed to the same degree as on Windows 9x/2K/XP.  I know, because I spent a few hours trying to get Classic to look like Rainy Day, and failed.  I also tried some official and unofficial &quot;themes&quot; for Windows 7 (Aero) that claimed to be &quot;much like Rainy Day&quot; but either did not work or required all the bells/whistles be turned on (along with making use of the horrible glass effect that you and I both find annoying :-) ).<br /><br />Before I left MS, I took notes of what my UI settings were.  I had to write all these down by hand with the help of a co-worker, but I got them all.  This is about &quot;as good as I could get it&quot; -- and we were using Firefox 3.x (for reasons I'd rather not get into) so the aforementioned Firefox UI issue was not a problem.  I'll put the details at the bottom of this post.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Go try to use Gnome 3 and you'll see what is a horrible GUI.</div><br />Regardless if GNOME 3 sucks or not, the fact of the matter is we're running out of choices on Windows.  Windows Vista and 7 destroy customisation capability, and Windows 8 inhibits it even more.  This might work for generic users who have no idea how to use a computer, but for technically-inclined users this is a hindrance.  Hell, even my own mother -- who is a generic end user by all means, and is in her late 50s -- cannot stand all the bells and shitwhistles of Windows 7, but finds the UI to look even worse if she goes with Classic.  She's tried for the past 5 years as well to get used to it, and has &quot;mostly&quot; adapted,but there are still many things she rants to me about when I'm on the phone with her about some computer issue.<br /><br />Anyway, here's my notes, circa March 2012:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">$ ls -l w7<br />-rw-------&nbsp; &nbsp; 1 jdc&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;users&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2956 Mar&nbsp; 9&nbsp; 2012 w7<br /><br />$ cat w7<br />Issues with Windows 7<br />=======================<br />- Microsoft buggered the busy cursor animation<br />&nbsp; http://www.istartedsomething.com/20090815/windows-7-busy-cursor-misses-a-beat/<br />- Removal of adjustable settings when using Windows Classic; all settings under<br />&nbsp; Appearance are adjustable but *do not actually change anything*<br />- Removal of Colour Schemes when using Windows Classic, such as Rainy Day.<br />&nbsp; Imitation themes online require Windows 7 theme hacks (which violate SFC),<br />&nbsp; and some just look like plain crap<br />- Disabling ClearType does not do so universally in the OS; many things still<br />&nbsp; force use of ClearType, such as bits/pieces of Control Panel and underlying<br />&nbsp; applets<br />- No volume licensing; activation (thus a phone call) required every time<br />&nbsp; hardware changes.&nbsp; &quot;Hacks&quot; are available for this but either cause more issues<br />&nbsp; than worth it, or require a custom bootloader/bootstrap (&quot;DaX method&quot;).<br /><br /><br />- Start with Aero enabled<br /><br /><br />Control Panel -&gt; Appearance and Personalisation -&gt; Personalise<br />================================================================<br />- Change desktop icons<br />&nbsp; - All checked EXCEPT Control Panel<br />- Change mouse pointers<br />&nbsp; - Scheme --&gt; None<br />- Desktop Background<br />&nbsp; - Set to whatever you want<br />- Sounds --&gt; No Sounds<br />- Window Colour<br />&nbsp; - Enable transparency unchecked<br />&nbsp; - Colour intensity&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; slider is maxed<br />&nbsp; - Colour mixer&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; green-blue-ish colour<br />&nbsp; - Advanced appearance settings<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Active Title Bar&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Microsoft Sans Serif, 8pt<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Application Background&nbsp; &nbsp; Color 1 RGB: 115,115,115<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Border Padding&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 0px<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Caption Buttons&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;18px<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Icon&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Microsoft Sans Serif, 8pt<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Inactive Title Bar&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Microsoft Sans Serif, 8pt<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Menu&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Microsoft Sans Serif, 8pt<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Message Box&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Microsoft Sans Serif, 8pt<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Palette Title&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Microsoft Sans Serif, 8pt<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Scrollbar&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;16px<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Selected Items&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Microsoft Sans Serif, 8pt<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Tooltip&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Microsoft Sans Serif, 8pt<br /><br />Control Panel -&gt; Appearance and Personalisation -&gt; Fonts<br />==========================================================<br />- Adjust ClearType text<br />&nbsp; - Turn on ClearType --&gt; UNCHECKED<br />&nbsp; - Click &quot;Next&quot; through all defaults<br /><br />Control Panel -&gt; System and Security -&gt; System -&gt; Advanced System Settings<br />============================================================================<br />- Performance -&gt; Settings<br />&nbsp; - All checkboxes UNCHECKED except:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - desktop composition<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Show transluscent selection rectangle<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Show window contents while dragging<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Use drop shadows for icon labels on the desktop<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; - Use visual styles on windows and buttons<br /><br />Desktop Properties<br />====================<br />- View -&gt; Small icons<br /><br />Taskbar Properties<br />====================<br />- Use small icons --&gt; checked<br />- Notification Area -&gt; Customise<br />&nbsp; - Always show all icons and notifications on taskbar --&gt; checked<br />- Toolbars<br />&nbsp; - Quick Launch --&gt; you get to deal with finding out how you did this :D<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; http://www.howtogeek.com/howto/windows-7/add-the-quick-launch-bar-to-the-taskbar-in-windows-7/<br /></div>

		

